external_knowledge:
- "top-funded candidates" refers to candidates ranked by total funding in descending order;
- "total funding" is the sum of the money raised and spent on the campaign;
- "average funding" is the average total funding of all candidates.

- "Strongest in terms of representation" refers to the party with the highest ratio of representatives to registered voters;
- "Elected representatives" are the individuals who have won seats in the political body;
- "Registered voters" are citizens who are eligible to vote and have registered to do so.

- "governors" refers to individuals who are in charge of a state or region;
- "parties" refers to political organizations that field candidates for public office;
- "elections" refers to the process of selecting public officials by voting;
- "voter turnout" is the percentage of eligible voters who cast a ballot in an election;
- "avg_voter_turnout_percentage" is the average of the voter turnout percentages across multiple elections;
- "max_voter_turnout_percentage" is the highest voter turnout percentage recorded in any single election.

- 'representation' refers to the number of representatives in a district;
- 'competition' refers to the number of candidates running in a district;
- The query considers both the number of representatives and candidates to determine the most politically active district.

- The term "representatives" refers to elected officials in a state's legislative body;
- The term "districts" refers to geographic areas that each representative represents;
- The ratio "representatives per district" is calculated by dividing the number of representatives by the number of districts in a state.
